682–Male":"1682–Deceased","1687–Female":"1687–Deceased","1652–1705":"1652–1705","08 NOV 1687":"8 November 1687","26 FEB 1682":"26 February 1682","1682":"1682","1680":"1680","20 November 1687":"20 November 1687","1689":"1689","1744":"1744","1688":"1688","1687":"1687","25 November 1705":"25 November 1705","1652":"1652","23 FEB 1678":"23 February 1678","1651":"1651","1716":"1716","1705":"1705","about 1680":"about 1680","St James' Duke's Place, London, England, United Kingdom":"St James' Duke's Place, London, England, United Kingdom","Cecil, Maryland, British America":"Cecil, Maryland, United States","Bishopsgate, London, England, United Kingdom":"Bishopsgate, London, England, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","Saint Botolph Bishopsgate,London,London,England, United Kingdom":"Bishopsgate, London, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Netherton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon): habitational name from one or more of the many minor places called Netherton in Devon (the placename occurs in the parishes of Berry Pomeroy, Buckland Monachorum, Combe Martin, Farway, Haccombe, Hartland, Sherford, and Staverton), or from one or more of the other places in England called Netherton, found in Worcestershire, Northumberland, Lancashire, and Yorkshire. All of these placenames derive from Middle English <i>nether</i> ‘lower’ + <i>toun</i> ‘settlement’ (Old English <i>neothera</i>, <i>tūn</i>)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed 